To simplify the given expression, we can rewrite each term using the definitions of $\csc \theta, \sin \theta, \cot \theta,$ and $\tan \theta.$ We have \begin{align*}
\frac{\csc \theta}{\sin \theta} - \frac{\cot \theta}{\tan \theta} &= \frac{1/\sin \theta}{\sin \theta} - \frac{\cos \theta/\sin \theta}{\sin \theta/\cos \theta} \\
&= \frac{1}{\sin^2 \theta} - \frac{\cos^2 \theta}{\sin^2 \theta} \\
&= \frac{1 - \cos^2 \theta}{\sin^2 \theta}.
\end{align*}Since $\sin^2 \theta + \cos^2 \theta = 1,$ we obtain $1 - \cos^2 \theta = \sin^2 \theta,$ so the expression is equal to \begin{align*}
\frac{\sin^2 \theta}{\sin^2 \theta} = \boxed{1}.
\end{align*}

The answer to this question is \boxed{1}.

