To find the probability that he flips more Heads than Tails, we need to find the probabilities of him flipping 2 Heads and 1 Tail or 3 Heads.

The probability of getting a Head is $60\%$ or $\frac{3}{5}$, and the probability of getting a Tail is $40\%$ or $\frac{2}{5}$.

Now we can calculate the probabilities.

The probability of getting 2 Heads and 1 Tail is ${3 \choose 2}\cdot\left(\frac{3}{5}\right)^2\cdot\frac{2}{5}$. There are ${3 \choose 2} = 3$ ways to choose which flip will be a Tail.

\begin{align*}
P(2\ Head,1\ Tail)&=3\cdot\left(\frac{3}{5}\right)^2\cdot\frac{2}{5}\\
&=\frac{54}{125}
\end{align*}

The probability of getting 3 Heads is $\left(\frac{3}{5}\right)^3$.

\begin{align*}
P(3\ Head)&=\left(\frac{3}{5}\right)^3\\
&=\frac{27}{125}
\end{align*}

Finally, we add these probabilities together to get our answer.

\begin{align*}
P(more\ Heads\ than\ Tails)&=P(2\ Head,1\ Tail)+P(3\ Head)\\
&=\frac{54}{125}+\frac{27}{125}\\
&=\frac{81}{125}
\end{align*}

The answer to this question is \boxed{\frac{81}{125}}

